WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.070
Good evening, everybody.

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:11.960
I'm Homi Bhaba, director of
the Mahindra Humanities Center,

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:14.510
and I'm absolutely
delighted to welcome you

00:00:14.510 --> 00:00:20.480
to the launch of the second
year of our environment forum.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:23.220
Last year's wide array
of events, including

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:27.860
visits by Terry Tempest
Williams, Jedediah Purdy, Roy

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:32.000
Scranton, Timothy LeCain,
Tiya Miles, and it's

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.970
an honor for us to have
our colleague Naomi

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:38.330
Oreskes to lead off this fall.

00:00:38.330 --> 00:00:42.410
Before Robin Kelsey
introduces Professor Oreskes,

00:00:42.410 --> 00:00:46.040
I wanted to share a few
thoughts on the series

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:51.510
and its importance for us
at the Mahindra Center.

00:00:51.510 --> 00:00:57.000
The forum is our attempt to
establish platforms that deal

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.940
with areas of study and public
interests that do not fall

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:07.410
within the remit of
any one discipline,

00:01:07.410 --> 00:01:13.520
and that we cannot simply in a
facile way designate as being

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:16.720
interdisciplinary.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:20.350
The fine granularity
of these problems

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:25.750
often emerges in the spaces
in between established bodies

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:27.440
of knowledge.

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:31.250
And this is something that
we're very keen on fostering

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:33.900
and exploring at the
Humanities Center,

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:36.710
these forms of
interstitial knowledge

00:01:36.710 --> 00:01:40.730
that question the boundaries
of several disciplinary

00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:42.620
configurations.

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:45.540
And out of them
emerge challenges

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:50.930
where we've got to find a
kind of montage of methods

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:55.310
in order to gain some
purchase or perspective.

00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:59.990
And the environment forum
really helps us to do this.

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:04.970
You have people who write in
the first person about processes

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:09.050
that are so much larger than any
first person narrative can ever

00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:10.370
contain.

00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:14.060
So there's this
remarkable energy

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:19.030
between specifying something
that has not been named

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:23.420
and putting around it several
dynamics of knowledge,

00:02:23.420 --> 00:02:26.990
subjectification, questions
of value, and so on.

00:02:26.990 --> 00:02:29.900
So it's this kind
of interstitial area

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:33.090
for which we really
thank our conveners

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:35.850
of the environmental forum.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:41.600
And I say this because it's been
my growing sense of what we do

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:45.320
here at the environment forum.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:47.420
Working with these
interstitial spaces

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:55.040
redefines the relationship
between pedagogical interest

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:58.300
and political action.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:00.170
So it's not simply
that we're dealing

00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:03.630
with a certain way in which
new knowledge is formed,

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:07.970
but it restructures the
articulation of education

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:11.720
and practice and the form
of political calculation

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:14.160
and judgment.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:16.230
The study of the
environment presents us

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:19.110
with the challenge
of having to secure

00:03:19.110 --> 00:03:24.600
a language of description that
finds its network, its voice,

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:30.480
in a continually circulating
network of dialogues.

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:32.580
The dominant motif
of these events

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:37.810
has been the profound issue
of the care of the planet,

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:42.460
[INAUDIBLE],, a form of care
that Heidegger, amongst others,

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:46.710
has elaborated in being in time.

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:50.980
Care as a form of ethical
attention and vigilant

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:55.570
interpretation is at the
very core of the project

00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:57.490
of the humanities.

00:03:57.490 --> 00:04:00.550
And to the extent to
which an ethic of care

00:04:00.550 --> 00:04:05.560
is fundamental to the
survival of planetary life,

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:08.860
the environment
forum is at the core

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:13.060
of the work of the
Mahindra Center.

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:15.040
I don't think that
there has ever

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:22.730
been a time which has made
this whole question of care

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:29.270
as an ethical, but also as
a careful textual project

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:32.850
more urgent or apparent.

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:35.820
There is such a
widespread carelessness

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:38.700
of the lives of the
people, a carelessness

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:42.820
towards the planet, a
carelessness towards truth,

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:45.960
a carelessness
towards interpretation

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:53.870
coupled in the last months
with remarkable ecological and

00:04:53.870 --> 00:04:56.300
environmental crises.

00:04:56.300 --> 00:05:04.040
It's almost as if nature
is standing up and saying,

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:06.900
we cannot have this any longer.

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:11.550
And in these crises,
what becomes visible

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:17.170
are the great deficits
of planetary care,

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:24.790
but also the great deficits
of citizenly carefulness.

00:05:24.790 --> 00:05:27.190
And it is in that
spirit that I'm

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:29.230
very happy to welcome
you to the launch

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:32.620
event of the second year
of the environment forum,

00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:36.430
and I want to thank my dear
friends and colleagues Robin

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.450
Kelsey and Ian
Miller for helping

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:43.364
us to build this argument.

00:05:43.364 --> 00:05:44.846
Thank you.

00:05:44.846 --> 00:05:47.810
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:57.220 --> 00:06:01.140
I'm Robin Kelsey, dean
of Arts and Humanities,

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:05.070
And with Ian Miller a
co-convener of the environment

00:06:05.070 --> 00:06:08.430
forum, the mission
of which has just

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:12.000
been articulated with
unprecedented eloquence

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.570
by Homi Bhaba.

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:17.790
And I want to thank Homi for
embracing the environment

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:21.180
forum, for coming
to these events,

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:23.590
for thinking hard
about this project,

00:06:23.590 --> 00:06:28.350
and for on this occasion
such a brilliant articulation

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:31.260
of what we are about.

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:36.540
I also want to thank Steve
Biel and Sarah Razor, who have

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.101
done so much to bring this on.

00:06:39.101 --> 00:06:39.600
Yes.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:48.260
[APPLAUSE] I am convinced there
is more than one Sarah Razor,

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:53.010
but she always
looks much the same.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:58.830
So this university, 391
years old and counting,

00:06:58.830 --> 00:07:04.960
has a motto that consists
of a single word, veritas.

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:09.610
Harvard presumably
pursues many values,

00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:14.230
but the isolation in our
motto of this one value,

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:18.730
truth, implicitly
acknowledges how easy

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:23.080
it would be to muddy
our own waters,

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:27.400
to lose our sense of
direction and purpose,

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:31.810
to drift down some easier path.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:37.890
The Harvard motto I think
rightly understood tacitly

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:40.380
recognizes that the
pursuit of truth

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:45.240
requires grit and courage
as well as curiosity.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:48.570
And no one at Harvard
exemplifies this combination

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:52.680
of qualities better
than Naomi Oreskes.

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:54.960
Professor of the history
of science at Harvard

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:57.090
as well as an
affiliate of the earth

00:07:57.090 --> 00:07:59.730
and planetary sciences,
Professor Oreskes

00:07:59.730 --> 00:08:05.040
has, by virtue of her gritty
and courageous pursuit of truth,

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:10.290
become a crucial agent of
our collective conscience.

00:08:10.290 --> 00:08:13.630
Along with her frequent
co-author Eric Conway,

00:08:13.630 --> 00:08:19.230
a historian at the Jet
Propulsion Lab at Caltech,

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:23.040
Professor Oreskes has clarified
the state of our knowledge

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.280
about human-induced
climate change,

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:29.250
exposed the hidden
apparatus that

00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:33.570
obfuscates and misrepresents
that knowledge,

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:36.870
and has offered a
bleak but all too sober

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:41.700
assessment of where our
carelessness, to use

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:47.460
Homi's term, may lead
our planet and ourselves.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:49.840
With respect to climate
change, in other words,

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:53.230
if we have any grasp
of where things stand

00:08:53.230 --> 00:08:55.620
and the challenges
we face, we owe it

00:08:55.620 --> 00:09:00.940
in no small part to
Professor Oreskes.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:04.360
A holder of a BS degree from
the Royal School of Mines--

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:07.510
I did not know this
actually before I started

00:09:07.510 --> 00:09:08.810
preparing this introduction.

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:10.900
I found that an absolutely
delightful piece

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:11.770
of information.

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:15.340
A holder of a BS degree from the
Royal School of Mines Imperial

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:19.850
College of London, and a
PhD from Stanford, Professor

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:23.950
Oreskes is the author or
co-author of several books,

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:26.410
and a common thread
running through them

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:29.170
is an insistence
on understanding

00:09:29.170 --> 00:09:32.880
how the production of
knowledge and the contestation

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:36.700
that that production
entails actually happens.

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:42.300
Along with other leading
historians of science,

00:09:42.300 --> 00:09:45.230
she has countered a
longstanding tendency

00:09:45.230 --> 00:09:50.480
to confuse the justification
for scientific theories

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:54.380
with the histories by which
those theories have obtained

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:57.020
their scientific standing.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:00.380
In her first book, The Rejection
of Continental Drift, Theory

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:04.020
and Method in American
Earth Science,

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:07.550
She argues convincingly
that a significant portion

00:10:07.550 --> 00:10:11.660
of this confusion stems from
an excessively monolithic

00:10:11.660 --> 00:10:14.870
understanding of the
scientific method.

00:10:14.870 --> 00:10:19.040
Indeed, she demonstrates
that American geoscientists

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:23.210
were so resistant to the
theory of continental drift

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:26.750
precisely because it
challenged the way that they

00:10:26.750 --> 00:10:28.700
went about their work.

00:10:28.700 --> 00:10:31.370
It's a wonderful
piece of scholarship

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:33.290
in the history of science.

00:10:33.290 --> 00:10:36.770
Working with Conway,
Professor Oreskes

00:10:36.770 --> 00:10:41.720
produced the 2010 book
Merchants of Doubt,

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:46.220
a phrase that has entered
the lexicon of many of us.

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:49.280
A book that demonstrated that
a small number of scientists

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:56.090
with strong ties to industry
and to industry-friendly parts

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:59.870
of our political establishment
have over decades served

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:04.220
to obscure scientific
consensus and sew

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:06.620
doubts in the populace
at large about

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:09.950
robust scientific inferences.

00:11:09.950 --> 00:11:13.910
The coterie of experts,
scientists of high standing

00:11:13.910 --> 00:11:17.750
who have, however, no
particular expertise

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:21.560
in the matter in question,
has time and again slowed

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:25.760
political recognition of a
range of dangerous practices

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:29.040
from cigarette smoking
to fossil fuel burning.

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:34.010
And as we experience the
onset of post-truth politics,

00:11:34.010 --> 00:11:36.840
Merchants of Doubt is
more important than ever.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:38.270
And I'm very much
looking forward

00:11:38.270 --> 00:11:44.300
to seeing how this segue
is made this evening.

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:47.120
More recently,
Oreskes and Conway

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:49.550
wrote The Collapse of
Western Civilization, a View

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:52.550
From the Future, a work
of speculative fiction

00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:56.360
that makes vivid the possible
costs of our ongoing failure

00:11:56.360 --> 00:11:59.750
to address our climate problem.

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:01.760
And I know Ian uses
this in his teaching

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:03.230
and has wonderful
stories to tell

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:06.890
about how generative it is.

00:12:06.890 --> 00:12:09.170
In addition to her
books, Professor Oreskes

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:12.140
has produced numerous articles
both in scholarly journals

00:12:12.140 --> 00:12:14.540
and the popular press.

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:19.190
She is a public intellectual
of the most necessary kind,

00:12:19.190 --> 00:12:23.690
and she is here this evening to
talk to us about giant power.

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:25.790
A giant power herself,
please join me

00:12:25.790 --> 00:12:27.588
in welcoming Naomi Oreskes.

00:12:27.588 --> 00:12:30.576
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:43.130
Thank you very much for
that incredibly generous

00:12:43.130 --> 00:12:44.090
introduction.

00:12:44.090 --> 00:12:46.473
But as you can see,
I'm not giant at all.

00:12:46.473 --> 00:12:48.320
[LAUGHTER] But on
the other hand, I did

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:51.440
pick up some grit at the
Royal School of Mines.

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:56.630
So it's really a pleasure to be
here and see so many new faces.

00:12:56.630 --> 00:12:58.640
And also it's great
to be introduced

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:03.050
as a poster child
for interstitiality

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:05.687
because earlier in my career I
was just considered a problem.

00:13:05.687 --> 00:13:07.520
You know, deans didn't
know where to put me.

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:09.520
One dean once told me I
had the strangest resume

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:10.790
he'd ever seen.

00:13:10.790 --> 00:13:12.410
So it's actually
incredibly gratifying

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:17.360
to feel that the world has kind
of come around to my vision.

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:18.930
So thank you very much.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:20.640
I'm feeling very
satisfied tonight.

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:21.890
Of course, that's a bad thing.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:23.431
You should never
feel self-satisfied.

00:13:23.431 --> 00:13:25.350
So with that, we get to work.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:28.010
So many of you are familiar
with the comedian John Oliver.

00:13:28.010 --> 00:13:29.970
And some of you may
have seen the routine

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:32.750
he did a few months back
where he got really vexed

00:13:32.750 --> 00:13:35.600
about the fact that many
Americans don't accept

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:37.400
the reality of climate change.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:39.560
And he noted that
one in four Americans

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:41.920
are skeptical-- or is
skeptical-- about climate

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:42.420
change.

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:44.720
And he said, "who gives a shit?

00:13:44.720 --> 00:13:45.930
That doesn't matter.

00:13:45.930 --> 00:13:48.420
You don't need people's
opinion on a fact.

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:51.530
You might as well have a poll
asking which number is bigger,

00:13:51.530 --> 00:13:53.780
5 or 15?

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:55.790
Do owls exist?

00:13:55.790 --> 00:13:59.030
Or are there hats?"

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:02.630
Now although I love John Oliver,
unfortunately as a historian

00:14:02.630 --> 00:14:05.480
I have to acknowledge that there
is, in fact, a long history

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:09.020
of arguing about whether
there are hats, so to speak,

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:12.320
and of trying to persuade
the American people that five

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:15.650
actually might be a
bigger number than 15.

00:14:15.650 --> 00:14:17.660
So just to give you one
example out of my work

00:14:17.660 --> 00:14:19.290
on the history of
climate change,

00:14:19.290 --> 00:14:21.960
Oliver was of course
referring to climate change,

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:24.980
and in particular he has
gone on several rants

00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:26.840
about the recent
claim that many of us

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:30.410
heard repeatedly during the
last election, the claim

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:34.100
that global warming
had stopped in 1998.

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:36.670
Now, these are the actual
historic temperature records

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:38.500
going back to 1880.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.410
But one thing we know
is that you can actually

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:44.440
get people to think about
numbers in very different ways

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:46.810
simply by the way
you present them.

00:14:46.810 --> 00:14:49.120
So for example, my
colleague Steve Lewandowski

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:51.997
did an extremely interesting
experiment a few years ago.

00:14:51.997 --> 00:14:53.580
These are the global
temperature data,

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:57.880
again, going back to 1880,
plotted in this graph showing

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:00.870
a five year running mean.

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:04.450
But he labeled it world
agricultural output.

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:09.910
And he asked people this,
what is the trend since 1998?

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:12.770
And they all answered that
output continued to rise,

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:14.670
which is the correct answer.

00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:16.500
But if you show
them this graph, you

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:18.160
get a very different answer.

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.100
This is what we call
the skeptic's graph

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:21.460
of global warming.

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:25.320
If you show them this, people
will tell you they don't know

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:27.240
or the temperatures didn't rise.

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:30.180
So this presentation is used
by many climate change skeptics

00:15:30.180 --> 00:15:32.160
and deniers to confuse
people about what's

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:37.800
actually happening with the
numbers, 5 and 15, or 1 and 2.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:39.990
Put more generally,
we have ample evidence

00:15:39.990 --> 00:15:43.050
that it's actually pretty easy
to get people arguing about

00:15:43.050 --> 00:15:44.980
whether or not there are hats.

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:47.130
Now, how do you
get people to argue

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:49.260
about the existence
of hats is largely

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:51.540
a social scientific question.

00:15:51.540 --> 00:15:54.420
But why people have
done so and for what

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:57.480
purposes I want to argue
is primarily a question

00:15:57.480 --> 00:15:59.280
of history and culture.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:03.090
And so today I want to
talk about the new work

00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:06.477
I'm doing on the history of
disinformation long duree.

00:16:06.477 --> 00:16:09.060
And I was hoping David Armitage
was here so that I could boast

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:10.830
about doing long duree history.

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:13.080
But in any event--

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:16.267
and to talk about it
specifically in the relation

00:16:16.267 --> 00:16:18.600
to the question of the defense
of free market capitalism

00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:19.622
in the United States.

00:16:19.622 --> 00:16:22.080
Because it turns out that these
two things are very closely

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:22.865
related.

00:16:22.865 --> 00:16:24.240
So I'm going to
talk to you today

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:27.090
about a new project
that I call Inventing

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:29.160
the Magic of the Marketplace.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:32.910
We could also call it the long
history of post-facticity.

00:16:32.910 --> 00:16:35.220
I'm particularly interested
in post-facticity

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:36.882
in the private sector.

00:16:36.882 --> 00:16:39.090
That is to say I'm not that
interested in the history

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:43.050
of politicians lying, I
think that's pretty familiar.

00:16:43.050 --> 00:16:45.900
But there's a different history
that I think is extremely

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:49.050
important of actors in the
private sector-- businessmen,

00:16:49.050 --> 00:16:52.416
PR, advertising
companies, think tanks--

00:16:52.416 --> 00:16:53.790
who have been
involved in this it

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:56.680
turns out for a very long time.

00:16:56.680 --> 00:16:58.920
So some initial observations.

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:01.260
This pattern of private
sector disinformation

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:05.430
is repeatedly linked to two
key and interrelated aims.

00:17:05.430 --> 00:17:08.160
One is to stop or
limit regulation

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:12.030
of particular industries such
as electricity or tobacco,

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:14.790
and the other is to
protect the private sector

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:18.450
from responsibility for
external costs of their products

00:17:18.450 --> 00:17:22.500
like air pollution, water
pollution, climate change.

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:24.390
But the defense of
the private sector

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:26.220
through propaganda
and disinformation

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:29.100
has repeatedly involved
tropes of freedom

00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:32.220
and the American way of life,
and has been repeatedly linked

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:34.710
to the defense of
laissez faire capitalism

00:17:34.710 --> 00:17:36.240
in the early 20th century--

00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:39.850
or what we tend to call
neoliberalism later--

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:42.960
and the repeated argument
that the American way of life

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:46.140
is inextricably bound to
enterprise capitalism.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:48.060
So this is a cultural
question, and so that's

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:50.670
one reason why I was keen to
give this talk here tonight

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:52.800
at the Humanities Center.

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:55.500
Now, Robin already referred
to my work with Erik Conway.

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:59.760
In Merchants of Doubt, we showed
how this argument about freedom

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:01.950
and the American way of
life was developed and honed

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:05.340
by the tobacco industry, and
then how a group of actors

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:08.190
applied these arguments
to a set of issues

00:18:08.190 --> 00:18:11.340
in the late 20th century,
including acid rain, the ozone

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:16.830
hole, the regulation of DDT,
and of course, climate change.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:19.350
We identified a specific
strategy which we saw

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:22.530
used repeatedly, to
cast doubt on facts

00:18:22.530 --> 00:18:25.170
that show the harms
of your product,

00:18:25.170 --> 00:18:27.960
insist that the
science is unsettled,

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:30.660
to recruit experts to give
your otherwise obviously

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:33.570
self-interested
position credibility,

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:35.880
to impugn the motives
of your opponents,

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:39.360
and to assert that their actions
threaten American freedom,

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:41.640
hence the use of the
term watermelons,

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:46.750
that they're green on the
outside but red on the inside.

00:18:46.750 --> 00:18:49.020
So in our research, we
traced these arguments

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:51.510
from current and recent
debates about climate change

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:53.454
back to the tobacco industry.

00:18:53.454 --> 00:18:54.870
And we showed
through our research

00:18:54.870 --> 00:18:57.240
how the same think
tanks, the same PR

00:18:57.240 --> 00:19:01.170
firms, the same advertising
agencies, and sometimes

00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:03.540
even the same
people were involved

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:06.360
in attacking the science
showing the harms of tobacco

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:08.580
and the science showing
the harms of fossil fuel

00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:10.170
combustion.

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.990
And we showed how they linked
the defense of harmful products

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:15.870
to the defense of free market
capitalism, and from there

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:18.440
to the defense of
freedom generally.

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:21.090
So just to give one example,
this is one of my favorite ones

00:19:21.090 --> 00:19:24.180
from a report defending
the tobacco industry

00:19:24.180 --> 00:19:27.900
and attacking the science
related to secondhand smoke.

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:31.260
The scientists who
wrote this piece, one

00:19:31.260 --> 00:19:34.290
of our merchants of doubt,
actually laid it on the line

00:19:34.290 --> 00:19:36.570
and he wrote, quote,
"if we do not carefully

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:39.750
delineate the government's
role in regulating dangers,

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:41.430
there's essentially
no limit to how much

00:19:41.430 --> 00:19:44.197
government can ultimately
control our lives."

00:19:44.197 --> 00:19:45.780
So there's the
argument in a nutshell,

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:48.390
and people often ask me,
well, are these people

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:49.546
just shills for industry?

00:19:49.546 --> 00:19:50.670
How do they sleep at night?

00:19:50.670 --> 00:19:52.730
How do they understand
what they're doing?

00:19:52.730 --> 00:19:53.990
It's a complicated story.

00:19:53.990 --> 00:19:55.870
The answer is not the
same for everyone.

00:19:55.870 --> 00:19:58.350
But I think this
argument helps to explain

00:19:58.350 --> 00:20:00.060
how people can take
these positions

00:20:00.060 --> 00:20:01.500
and view them as principled.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:07.910
But although it may be
principled for an individual,

00:20:07.910 --> 00:20:10.890
it gets used in an
extremely unprincipled way.

00:20:10.890 --> 00:20:13.610
So I thought I would just show
you a small clip from our film,

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:15.500
from the film version
of Merchants of Doubt,

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:18.110
because I'm an extremely
lucky academic.

00:20:18.110 --> 00:20:21.340
If you don't read my book,
I can show you the movie.

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:23.720
So I'm going to just show
you a clip that really shows

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:27.440
how this argument about freedom
was exploited by the tobacco

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:29.630
industry, and then
we'll move on to looking

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:32.304
at this longer older history.

00:20:32.304 --> 00:20:35.286
